<br>
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
The man in the tattered, black cloth and hood walked throught the small village at night. He stopped in the middle of the village and slowly turned from one side to the other, looking around himself at all the surroundings. Houses made of wood and hopes; a well in the middle of the village and a large, single windmill for grinding wheat. The sound of the cloth blades of the windmill turning in the strong breeze and the rustle of the trees was all the man could hear. The guards had fallen asleep from the special blend of herbs the man in the tattered cloak had given them to smoke. A &quot;gift&quot; as he befriended them with small talk of crops and women.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
The boy sat up in bed, determined to be brave like his father, a ranger of the elves of Kelethin. The boy's family had moved away from the elven homeland, to trade and prosper before returning to Kelethin, home of the wood elves. <br>
<br>
The boy found himself facing a man. A man sitting on the chair in the corner of the small room, watching the boy silently in the dark. He was a human wearing black cloth that draped over his body like a long cape, with the hood pulled up over his head, hiding his upper features with shadow. The boy's elven eyes could see the man in the dark of the room, yet the shadow under the hood still hid most of the man's face. From what the boy could see, the man was clean shaven, with strong features and piercing grey eyes. <br>
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
The man in the black cloth and hood, slowly walked through the small village. He placed small amounts of special herbs near each home. The smell of the herbs carried by the breeze to spread throughout the village. People asleep and resting, fell deeper into the dark behind their eyelids, from which they could not awake. <br>
The stranger stood still. <br>
Unmoving. <br>
Waiting with an inhuman patience, for the herbs to take their full effect. <br>
Standing still like a statue in black, in the center of the village.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
The elven boy did not cry out in alarm. He wanted to be a hero and fight this stranger himself. The reality of him being a boy who stood little chance of fighting an adult, did not occur to him. Dreams of courage and not believing in their own mortality, made children brave. The man in the black cloth and hood slowly started to talk in a low, cultured voice.<br>
<br>
&quot;You will one day be a hero, who did not wish to be anything but a simple person with a simple life. You will one day rush into the darkness under a mountain, to save a village girl who became lost. You will lose a part of your soul on purpose. You will make a deal with death and decay to save the life of the girl... when you find there are no options left in the dark under the mountain. In the dark, where even your beloved goddess cannot help you beyond the magic she gives you, for all people must walk life on their own, yet evil will always try to make a deal.&quot; The man's voice was strong and patient, with no rush to finish what he had to say.<br>
<br>
&quot;The girl will be saved and safe. The monsters under the mountain will not kill you...and you will become a monster.&quot; said the man in the dark. &quot;You will do terrible things, Relias.&quot; The boy could only listen, as he felt hypnotised by the voice. &quot;You will be known by another name and see through different eyes. A man with half a soul, lost on purpose to protect your own plans... which turn dark. A man who still has visions of sunlight and trees. A man who faintly remembers his past life as a faded dream.  A man who serves death.&quot; The stranger in the corner of the room stopped speaking and just watched the boy with grey eyes, then he was gone. The boy blinked his eyes and wondered if he was half awake with his mind still stuck in a dream.<br>
<br>
This was one hundred years ago.<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Hours had passed. The night was beginning to die as the sun struggled to be reborn. The bodies of the villagers hung from the trees like horrid decorations for a village faire. Some of them hung upside down, tied by the ankle. Others hung by the neck. Dead long before they were strung up like criminals to be executed. They never awoke, as the stranger plunged the dagger down swiftly through the darkness and rays of moonlight and into the villagers hearts.<br>
<br>
The man in the tattered, black cloth and hood, a funeral shroud stolen from a tomb of nobles, slowly walked with a calm demeanor out of the village of the murdered.<br>
<br>
<br>
Under a city of hope, in a hidden world of death and decay, the man in the black cloth and hood performed a spell. The spell came to life with a dagger that shed the blood of one hundred innocent victims. The man performing the spell was given a vision. A vision of how to create a powerful servant. To create a general for an army that would help the man take over the cult that trained him. An army to serve his will and his will alone. Defying even his master if needed. The man in the tattered shroud, walked out of the dark under the city and onto a road on the land above. The first step on a long journey.<br>
<br>
At a residence that is home to many dark souls and dark minds, there is a knock on the front door. A servant watching over the residence, opens the door and speaks to the guard of the front gates. A visitor arrived in the rain, in the middle of the day. A visitor who wishes to speak with a young woman of dark elven descent. The servant walks in the rain, hunched over and irritated, towards the front gate.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Who are you?&quot; the servant shouts. Trying to make his voice clear through the pounding of the rain. The stranger just stands there for a moment. Silent and unmoving. Wearing a tattered, black funeral shroud that functions as a cloak and hood. The upper half of his face hidden in the shadow of the hood; his grey eyes watching. The faintest hint of a smile is on his face. The faint smile of someone who knows somthing.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I wish to speak to the woman called Minru.&quot; said the stranger at the gates. His cultured voice patient, low but not deep. &quot;My name is Morcrin.&quot;<br>
<br>
