<br>
A raven cawed at him from an old tree growing over an even older grave. the mercenary looked up at the rain soaked bird. &quot;Not enough sense in ye to get out of the rain, eh?&quot; the mercenary chuckled. &quot;Stupid bird..&quot; he grumbled, then fished in his dirty pockets for a skipping stone to throw at the bird. Maybe if he hit it hard enough, he could have a little raven for dinner, instead of the swill at the local tavern. The raven cawed lowder at him, as if sensing his plans and becoming hostile itself. The mercenary snickered as he found and brought out the skipping stone. &quot;Stay right 'ere, little birdy. Ol' Gun is gonna just flip you this little stone and have some...&quot; the mercenary heard footsteps.<br>
<br>
&quot;She said, 'beloved, how art thou?'..she said to me.&quot; the  strange man covered in mud and walking among the graves whispered with a smile, as he approached the mercenary. Seemingly unaware or unconcerned for the sword at the mercenary's belt. &quot;What the Hate are you talkin'  'bout, you stupid man?&quot; the mercenary said in anger, dropping the stone and drawing his sword in one incredibly quick motion. The madman merely grinned with perfect teeth. He had a clean-shaven, handsome face some women would call beautiful. His eyes had an inner gleam that showed intensity and purpose. Cold with a smile. The strange man just stoped at the point of the mercenary's sword. Smiling, as the tip of the blade touched his throat and drew a faint drop of blood.<br>
<br>
&quot;He said I had a pretty face...&quot; stated a feminine voice behind the mercenary. Wistful and dreamy. <br>
The mercenary quickly moved to the side to keep the man in his sight but to also guard against a back attack. A slim woman in a dirty dress that used to be white, approached. Covering her face and upper body was a thin veil. A wedding veil, all muddy and tattered. The mercenary could see only a faint hint of her face behind the cloth but he could tell she was smiling. <br>
&quot;I said  ' thank you good sir. My name is Pretty Mary.  Would you like to touch me ? ' &quot; the woman said in her dream like voice. &quot;Then...I ate his face off.&quot; The woman lifted up the veil to reveal a beautiful face to make men dream... and teeth filed to sharp points. <br>
&quot;What the Hate is this?&quot; the mercenary yelled. &quot;You two lovers mad?&quot;<br>
&quot;Not mad...&quot; a deep voice said from the dark beyond two large gravestones. &quot;Quite the opposite, really. Quite bright, really. Quite deadly, really.&quot; the deep, grateing voice was far too intelligent to be coming from the creature that emerged from the shadows.  Eight feet tall. Red eyes that glowed out from under the shade of a black hood. Large, long ears that reached to a point. Grey chainmail and an ornate belt decorated with human skulls. The troll looked slightly different from others of it's kind. Almost like a dark, giant, green skinned version of the fey. His beastial face showed an unusual amount of intelligence. He carried a mace strapped to his side but had no other items on him that would belong to a fighter. Instead, he had pouches of spell components and bones. <br>
He was something that somehow existed but never should have been. A troll who learned the Dark Arts.  Not a Shadowknight but a true Necromancer.<br>
<br>
The mercenary stepped back in surprise. Briefly forgetting about the two strange humans when seeing and understanding what he saw before him. Pretty Mary let the veil drop back down. &quot; Black Vach...do you think he likes me?&quot; she said with a giggle as she carefully approached the mercenary. &quot;Malga, would the dirty man like to speak to my bones? &quot; she asked the troll, then turned back to the mercenary only to see him running toward the rusty gates. Black Vach, the handsome human with a mad smile, was already upon the mercenary. Moving fast like a cat and cutting the back of the mercenary's legs, with long fingernails that cut too deep for nails. More like blades. The troll, Malga Syn, roared in laughter as the mercenary fell down. The troll kept his face turned up to the heavens. Letting the rain fall into his large, shark like mouth.<br>
<br>
&quot;You didn't speak to my bones.&quot; Pretty Mary pouted, sounding sad. &quot;You didn't speak to my bones...and now they have something to say to you.&quot; <br>
Pretty Mary opened up her hand to reveal pieces of bone that began to glow. The bones then grew and flew out of her hand and formed into something unnatural. The mercenary tried to fight, waving his sword back and forth through the air. Crying out in defiance in the rain, as the skeletal pet of Mary, the man called Black Vach and the troll Necromancer closed in on him. The raven in the tree watched, as if pleased.<br>
